Preheat your oven to 200°C. Pick the @rosemary{1} leaves from their stalks and roughly
chop (discard the stalks). Chop the @salad potatoes{350%g} in half. Pop them onto
a #baking tray{} with half the rosemary. Drizzle with oil and season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}. Mix well to coat and lay out in a single layer. When 
your oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden and tender,
~{25-30%minutes}.

Meanwhile, peel and quarter the @pear{1} lengthways. Remove the core and halve
each quarter lengthways again. Pop into a #small bowl{} along with half of the
@honey{15%g} and a drizzle of oil.

> If your honey has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

Roughly chop the @walnuts{20%g}.

When the potatoes have been in the oven for ~{15%minutes}, pop the pears onto
the same #tray{} and roast until tender and starting to go golden,
~{10-12%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of oil in a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat.
When hot, lay the @venison leg steaks{2} into the pan and season with salt
and pepper. Brown the meat for ~{1%minute} on all sides. Lower the heat
slightly and cook for another ~{1%minute} on each side.

> Venison is best served rare but if you like it more well done, cook for another
  2 mins on each side.

> Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. The venison is safe to
  eat when the outside is browned.

Once cooked, rest the steaks on a #board{} loosely covered with #foil{}.

While the venison rests, pop the @wholegrain mustard{17%g}, @chicken stock paste{10%g},
@creme fraiche{75%g}, remaining rosemary and @water{50%ml} for the sauce into
the pan you cooked the venison in. Gently heat on medium-high until piping hot,
~{2-3%minutes}, stirring frequently.

Pop the @pea shoots{40%g} and roasted pear into a small bowl along with the
walnuts, remaining @honey{15%g} and the @cider vinegar{15%ml}. Season with
salt and pepper and mix together to coat the salad in the dressing.

When ready to eat, thinly slice the venison and serve on your plates with
the potatoes and pea shoot salad alongside. Pour the sauce over the venison to
finish. Enjoy!